description: This is an axial T2-weighted MRI image showing a brain with normal brain without any dementia (in healthy control).
This MRI image shows a normal hippocampus but severe parietal atrophy, suggesting Alzheimer's disease.
The MRI scan shows evidence of atrophy in the medial temporal lobe, suggesting Alzheimer's disease.
This MRI scan shows atrophy in the medial temporal lobe, suggesting the possibility of Alzheimer's disease.
This MRI image shows normal temporal lobes in a young individual, suggesting no abnormalities.

This is an MRI image showing an intermediate increase in the width of the choroid fissure, a slight increase in the width of temporal horn, with a slight decrease in the height of hippocampal formation, suggesting mild medial temporal lobe atrophy (MTA = 2).
The brain atrophy observed in this MRI is suggestive of Alzheimer's disease (AD).
This axial T2-weighted MRI image shows moderate volume loss in the left temporal lobe, which is suggestive of Alzheimer's disease.
This is an MRI image which highlights severe hippocampal atrophy, suggesting Alzheimer's disease (AD).
This MRI image shows a few small scattered lesions in the subcortical white matter and bilateral ventricles, suggesting Vascular dementia.

This coronal T2-weighted MRI image shows mildly prominent sulci and ventricles. Additionally, reduced volume of the bilateral hippocampi, amygdalae, and entorhinal cortex in this image can suggest Alzheimer's disease.

This coronal T1-weighted MRI image shows mildly prominent sulci and ventricles. Additionally, reduced volume of the bilateral hippocampi, amygdalae, and entorhinal cortex in this image can suggest Alzheimer's disease.
This is an MRI image highlighting frontotemporal lobar atrophy, which suggests behavioral frontotemporal dementia.
This is an MRI image showing no abnormalities in the choroid fissure, temporal horn, or hippocampal formation, suggesting no medial temporal lobe atrophy (MTA = 0). Alzheimer's disease is unlikely.
